# Type-checking violations for `fn main` signatures.
#
# The type-checker accepts exactly two shapes for `fn main`:
# `fn main()` (no parameters) and `fn main(exit: &out i32)` (single
# `&out i32` parameter).  Every other signature fires
# TC-MainBadSignature.
#
# Note: only one `fn main` may appear per source file — a second
# declaration fires TC-DuplicateDeclaration.  The two distinct
# violation paths (wrong parameter type vs. too many parameters)
# cannot be merged into one file.  This file covers the wrong-type
# branch because the diagnostic names the exact required type, making
# it the more precise regression anchor.  The extra-parameters branch
# (two or more params, firing on the function name span) was dropped
# as a less informative duplicate of the same diagnostic code.
#
#   fn      violation                DiagCode              trigger
#   ──────  ───────────────────────  ────────────────────  ──────────────────────────────
#   main    single wrong-type param  TC-MainBadSignature   &out i64 instead of &out i32

# ---------- main ----------

# A single parameter whose type is `&out i64` instead of `&out i32`
# fires TC-MainBadSignature naming the found type in the message.
fn main(exit: &out i64) {
  entry:
    exit.* = 0;
    return
}
